As to why your code fails to run here is what is happening:

When you run the code it runs from the top to bottom (first line to last line)

Since you are checking the condition in the loop once you leave that loop it just moves on to the next while loop never coming back to the one it just left.
 
So once you are past that while (input==8) it does not check for it again.

So after you enter 6 your program has reached its final loop which when fails exits the program

Hope you understood that. Feel free to ask if you don&#39;t.

While you&#39;re reading 8&#39;s, your code is stuck in the `while (input==8)` loop.
Then once the 6 arrives, it exits that loop and goes into the `while (input==6)` loop. At this point any digit except for 6 will exit that loop and terminate the program.

What you probably want instead is to replace the large number of small loops with a single one that keeps asking the user for his input, and printing the result of his choice. Something like:

    do{
       //display menu
       //read user&#39;s choice
       //react to user&#39;s choice
    }while(input != 0)

Think of how a `while` loop actually works. It will continue to repeat itself as long as a certain condition is `true`.

So in your first loop, `while (input == 8)`, if the user selects something other than `8`, the loop exits and your code continues.

But then you hit another loop, looking for another `input` value.  This means you start a loop for each possible entry.

Instead, you should have just one loop that keeps asking the user for input **until** they enter `0`.  Then, inside that loop, since we know they&#39;ve entered something other than 0, perform some `if` statements to figure out what they entered:

        Scanner keyboard = new Scanner(System.in);
